The Remembrance of Forgotten Villages in Cuba
With the introduction of the law of Álvaro Reynoso, almost hundreds of sugar cane factories in all of Cuba concluded the doors (photo: Julio Batista)
The popular village Gregorio Arleé Mañalich, located in the western Cuban province of Mayabeque, is commonly known as el Central - in Spanish sugar mill - notwithstanding that there is no significant sugar harvest on site.
It is two years since the activities in sugar cane factories have been paralyzed.
After exhaustion, the sugar cane industry remained silent in the region, and the factory gradually lost its facilities until only the scaffolding of steel and concrete remained.
About 272 workers had to reinvent themselves.
Some changed the work.
Others resigned and commute to the factories every day.
Nene, a soldier's veteran, who stands every day at 4: 00 a.m., the crisis in the sugar cane industry does not rob his sleep.
He heard that there are sugar cane factories in the east of the region, which are in operation after a long period of inactive time, because they have been preserved.
That was something he did not expect.
Nene recalls that in Mañalich the sugar cane factory would be preserved, but the promise was not kept.
The sugar cane industry withstood the plagues, the fall of socialism, the low market prices, inefficiency, poor management decisions and climate change.
In 2016, production amounted to 1.6 million tons of sugar, less than the amount produced in 1910.
The message would have been a concern for the country a few decades ago, but the bad harvests are not news anymore.
Why was the Cuban sugar cane industry off?
The old railway platform of the community saw even better times.
(photo: Julio Batista)
The reduction of the sugar cane industry was an economic necessity: the 155 sugar cane factories were technically outdated, and hardly competitive they became unsustainable for the country.
The initial idea was to concentrate production on the most efficient factories, the annual production objective was 4 million tonnes.
They left only the factories which could produce sugar for a maximum of 4 Centavos (0.03 Euro).
The solution to unemployment?
The motives that led to such measures were the low productivity of the sugar cane plantations and the sugar crisis in the world market.
Nevertheless, the price of sugar rose again about a decade ago.
From 2017 to 2025, the price of unrefined sugars will remain between 15 and 16 Centavos per pound, according to the 2016 report "Agricultural Prospects" issued by the OECD and FAO, the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organisation.
If the current production would reach the level of 2001 (3.6 million tonnes), raw sugar exports would generate about 85 million dollars for the country.
Not everything went well
"" "" "" "today's day will certainly go into history," "" "these were the first words of Cuban President Fidel Castro during his speech on 21 October 2002 at the sugar factory in Lavandero." ""
From then on the process of restructuring began in the sugar industry.
In the following years, the shutdown of 98 sugar cane factories, more than 65 million people, received their full salaries for further education.
The same happened in the sugar cane factory Gregorio Arlée Mañalich on May 14, 2004.
Luis Alberto Pérez has been working in the factory since 1967.
When Nene, as he is known as a soldier, speaks about the closure of the factory, the word he repeats most is "scam."
Almost all respondents said the same thing: not one of them was informed that the factory would be shut down.
In order for the place to be preserved, they formed a full-time working group.
Before the first year of the year, the first letters began to come.
It was official documents which differed only with regard to the parts that would be removed, the addressee and the date.
All were signed by Ulises Rosales del Toro, only the minister could approve any withdrawal.
From then on the responsibility was over and the letters came more and more frequently.
Juan Carlos Rivero was responsible for the shut-down factory for two years and he was one who received the letters. "the country had no money for the sugar cane mills that were still in operation," he insures.
Eddy Reyes, 64 years, is waiting for retirement in another plant, the Boris Luis Santa Coloma.
He was against his will in the decommissioning of the factory, in whose construction he helped.
With each part he removed, he dismounted one of his 31 years of work.
The most developed industrial area of Cuba and most important worktops was wiped out.
In many cases, there were no alternatives to the jobs and services generated in the communities in which they were located.
We will never know whether during the mammoth speech of October 21, 2002, the then President looked into the eyes of the people present when he guaranteed that for the areas whose factories were no longer in operation for five years, everything would go well.
The price of the population for the closure of sugar cane mills
Sugar cane has been extracted only high by milling since 2004.
(photo: Julio Batista)
After two years Gregorio Arleé Mañalich learned that many things change, but not always for the better when a factory is closed.
When the sugar cane factory closed, or rather, when they began to disregard it, they also stopped asphalting the road, which also disadvantaged other establishments.
Without work in the region, and with advanced age, Nene and Eddy had to look for other factories.
They became spare parts.
Without a perspective for the future, many young people also left the region.
In the area a food factory was created, whose production does not even serve for the supply of the community.
The ruins of the factory behind the new plant are still impressive.
At the end of 2016, Nene came back to the Boris Luis Santa Coloma plant, the ruins of the place where he began to work.
Forty-nine yields to the old soldier a pension of two thousand peso per month to spend the years in retirement in Mañalich.
Mr. Nene, a man of black skin color, small, with few teeth and clear voice, is not a supporting person, yet he does not give up the lies he told him.
They have tormented him for ten years.
Nene goes to retirement at age 65, not because he lacks strength, but because he is bittered.
