Created by Wikipedia (CC BY-SA 3.0)
For over a month now Turkey has been blocking the popular Encyclopedia of Wikipedia, based on the crowdsourcing principle.
Day after day, it becomes clear how important the platform is for users to find and share helpful information.
Both students and reporters and fans of TV series oppose the blockade.
Although many tech-savvy Internet users are used to use bypass tools for blocked web pages (a recent article from the New York Times reports that Turkey has the third largest VPN-prevalence of the world), most common Wikipedia users do not fall into this category.
Although Turkey has been blocking articles from Wikipedia since 2008, as has recently been described in a published report by the Berkman Klein Center for Internet & amp; Society at Harvard University has been taking place regular blockings since 2007, after the internet law (No. 5651) was adopted.
After China, Turkey is the second most famous country in the world when it comes to the massive censorship of Wikipedia.
While the platform remains locked, several Mirroring Pages (pages that reflect the content of Wikipedia and are frequently updated) are now surfaced.
A solution came from IPFS (the InterPlanetary File System), when the platform exposes all Turkish Wikipedia pages on its decentralized peer-to-peer network, which is not based on the system of domain names and thus makes a complete censorship difficult.
The content is, however, irrevocable in spite of legal prohibition.
In a blog post, IPFS reports about its efforts:
After listening to the news (about the locking of Wikipedia), we put all the snapshots from Wikipedia to the IPFS platform. thus, it is possible to read the content in a decentralized and distributed way.
This can help users to at least view all Wikipedia articles, even if they cannot reach the website www.wikipedia.org themselves.
IPFS also stated that this step was carried out independently from the Wikimedia Foundation, and it is merely screenshots and no live or dynamic versions of the website.
However, Wikimedia was involved in other efforts to circumvent the barrier.
Cristian Consonni of Wikimedia Italy has both tr.vikiansiklopedi.org, an aberrant page of Wikipedia, as well as WikiMirror, an open source project that everyone can use to host similar mise pages when locked in the respective country Wikipedia.
Consonni reported Subhashish Panigrahi - Global Voices Member and staff at Mozilla in the Panigrahi's Open Speaks "Podcast:
It is not a complete copy of a proxy address, a mirror.
One accesses to another URL, which is not the original. that which one sees then is from Wikipedia.
Essentially, the server further directs the request to the correct Wikipedia page, so that it is possible to see the content of Wikipedia itself when it is locked in Turkey.
Because this is done by a server not in Turkey.
