Rohini Paist has been working with the help of her video camera for seven years on the discovery of practices such as children's marriage to the exile of HIV and AIDS infected individuals, and leads these clubs.
It tells of how these clubs have created a safe place for these women and at the same time have made them ambassadors of change.
The first video that Rohini showed in her discussion was of women who do not call their husbands name.
She decided on this issue because she wanted to open the conversation about the Patriarchate with a problem with which women can easily identify.
Not to speak out loud on the names of their husbands, is a custom that they are fully responsible and never questioned.
Rohini means:
This tradition attests that a woman respects her husband and wishes him a long life.
A woman who does not consider this is considered as deceitful, a woman without morality.
The tradition is so deep-rooted that we never thought about this round of discussion.
At the beginning, Rohini, who had never called her husband at her name, wanted to try at home as it runs.
She showed the video of the discussion round her husband and her mother-in-law.
Rohini tells us:
My mother-in-law and my husband remained silent after the video was over.
"" "Prakash, my husband, turned to me and said I should call him now by his name." "" "" ""
With this confidence in luggage, Rohini started its first discussion club.
Many women had never heard the word "Patriarchate" before. some believed that it was a good thing because it meant that the younger members of a family, especially girls and women, would be protected.
At the beginning of the round, Rohini showed a video about the problem in Uttar Pradesh.
After the video projection, the women tried to get the discussion going.
Rohini asked every participant to tell her husband's name with different feelings - happy, angry, sad, affectionate and so on.
"" "then she asked all" "" "If we can't tell the name of our husbands, but they can call us how they want, does that mean they don't respect us?" ""
"" "should it not be equivalent?" "" "" ""
"some of these women have been married for 30 years and this was the first day to bring their husbands name over their lips," says Rohini Pawas from the village of Walhe in Maharashtra about breaking a century-old tradition in which married women can never pronounce the name of their husbands.
Rohini tells us:
A woman was so shy that she only kneaded in front of her during the whole exercise; another decided to release the whole strained frustration against him and his family by cursing him.
The expression on her faces was ecstatic.
I think I will never forget it again.
Still in an adrenalin rush about having broken with an ancient custom, the women decided that they would actually try to name their husbands at home.
And they kept their word.
In the coming days Rohini received a variety of reports.
The husband of a woman called Rohini and asked what ideas she put the women upside down: his wife could not stop telling his name.
