Why do we just write love letters to people we know?
Is it not even more important to accommodate people who feel expelled?
This is exactly what prompted the young Colombian activist Leonardo Párraga from the BogotArt Foundation and Cristian Palacios from the Young-Youth Foundation and inspired her to the campaign Cartas por la (Letters for Reconciliation), encouraging young people to write letters to guerrilla fighters.
Only recently their country was the scene of a historic event and they wanted to contribute their part: after years of negotiations, the Colombian government closed a peace treaty with the guerrilla movement FARC (German: revolutionary forces of Colombia), forming the end of the longest armed conflict in Latin America.
The signing of the peace treaty was considered to be so significant that the Colombian president Jose Manuel Santos received the Nobel Peace Prize for his merits.
But before Colombians there is still a long way to speak of real reconciliation and peace.
Guerrilla fighters who have lived in illegal camps for many years and have been exposed to war rhetoric and carried their arms around the clock must now re-integrate into life as civilians.
The Colombian society, which had become accustomed to life in constant fear and in some cases deep hatred against guerrilla fighters, must now take in its ranks and support them in building a new life.
Leonardo and Cristian were convinced that the young Colombians would have to join together and help in the process of integration.
And that's exactly what they did: up to now thousands of young people have already written letters - love messages to former guerilla fighters to welcome them back to society.
The aim of the campaign is 6900 letters - one for every former guerilla fighter - to be handed over personally.
Valentine's Day as an inspiration for the campaign
The idea for the letters to reconciliation arose at the World Summit of Nobel Peace Laureates, which took place in Bogotá in February 2017. there, Leonardo and Cristian had the opportunity to talk briefly to Kailash Satyarthi, who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2014.
This explained that we write thousands of love letters to the people we love on Valentine's Day but forget those who need them much more needless.
He was planning to share his love with people that needed the most urgent appeal this year.
So the plan was to write letters full of hope and support for former FARC fighters who now need to find their place in society and build a new life. "the letters will show that the Colombian society is ready to make the discourse of a history of war a common history of peace," she says.
So far more than 2,000 letters have been collected during the campaign.
The initiative is represented in all major cities of Colombia such as Cali, Manizales, Medellín, Barranquilla and Bogotá.
'i never thought that someone would forgive me '
The first 500 letters were delivered on 19 March in one of the UN camps in the region of Caldono-Cauca.
A group of 40 students from the University of Javeriana in Cali, two members of the Municipality of Cali and Leonardo of the BogotArt Foundation travelled to the camp to personally pass the letters.
The members of the FARC have set themselves up as they had done before to accept the commands of their leaders.
But this time they received no orders, but letters full of protection from people from all over the country.
It was a very moving moment for everyone involved. "it's incredible how many different feelings you can go through in just a few hours - from fear to happiness and everything in between," explained the political science student Manuela Jiménez Avila later.
Sandra Parra, an employee of the Governor of the Province of Valle del Cauca described this unforgettable experience as follows:
After passing the letters, a former warrior led me through the camp of the guerilla fighters.
