The self-burning of a man named Jassim Moramazi on August 27 drew the desperate situation of the Arab Ahwazi community in Iran, which is characterized by poverty and unemployment, into the limelight.
Moramazi was married and had a child; he lived in Al-Thawra in the region of Ahwaz in the southwest of Iran.
He suffered from anxiety, depression, and he was ashamed of his own helplessness, inability to pay for his family, so Ahwazi human rights groups who would like to work in Ahwaz and remain anonymous.
A video shared on YouTube kept the moments after he had lighted himself.
Some people quickly managed to erase the flames, and Moramazi was brought to Taleghani hospital in the city of Ahwaz.
According to local sources, the burns were so strong that the doctors couldn't do anything anymore.
He died shortly afterwards.
It was not the only suicide that happened in August within the Arab Ahwazi minority, and activists on the ground warn that even more men could take life.
The Ahwazi Centre for Human Rights announced that this month some others - Hamid Maniat, Ali Hazbawi, Sayed Falah Moussawi and Shahab ich Tamim - have appealed.
Their stories have one thing in common: they were all family-patrons, who were helpless and unable to feed their families because of the persecution by the Iranian government, to feed their families and to pursue a safe work.
Arab Ahwazi suffer from poverty, unemployment and discrimination
The region in which most of the Arab Ahwazi-based Arab communities living in Iran has been shaken by a profound economic crisis which makes it difficult for the domestic Arab population to make a living.
A century ago, the Arab Ahwaz was a predominantly autonomous region in Iran until the Pahlavi monarchy assumed power and in 1925 undertook great efforts to end ethnic autonomy throughout Iran.
In Ahwaz region, there are some of the largest oil and gas fields in Iran, as well as some of the most profitable and valuable usable areas for Iranian agriculture.
Despite these valuable resources, the regional economy continues to develop only slowly, and the local population is getting little from this wealth.
It is often victims of untreated diseases, hunger and privations.
The Iranian regime is denying the Ahwazi-Arabs systematically in the local oil, gas and petrochemical industries.
The government also built a large number of dams, the water from the Arab areas to the Persian territories, where the provinces of Isfahan, Yazd, Kerman and Ghom lie.
These dams have only led to aggravating the devastation caused in the region, and to destroy local agriculture as well as the fish and palm industries.
The unemployment rate among Arab ahawzi adolescents has now increased to 81%.
Nour Mohammed Pur, the Iranian Director General for Cooperative, Labour and Social Welfare, reported that 5% of Ahwazis who are looking for a job have completed primary school, 55% finished school, and 45% have completed a university degree.
