Medical research in Africa: opportunities and misunderstandings
Ranjit Warrier 2016 in Zambia, picture taken with his consent
Medical research in Africa is rarely mentioned in the media or not mentioned at all. it is a growing area that addresses one of the most pressing needs of the continent.
There are two reasons for the need for medical research carried out on site: there are many medicines and vaccines that are lacking in the global healthcare system, which cover the specific medical need on the African continent.
Diseases such as AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria have far more grave consequences in the poorest countries than elsewhere, and lack of investment in researching these diseases by drug companies is a major problem.
Second, the research carried out by African scientists is helping build their own research capacities in Africa. a greater role of science and technology can only be conducive to the economic growth of the continent.
Dr. Ranjit Warrier is Director of the Center for Infectious Diseases in Zambia (Centre for Infectious Disease Research in Zambia, CIDRZ).
In the 1990s he grew up in Lusaka, Zambia, especially when the AIDS epidemic had a serious impact on national health.
He left Zambia for a study in the United States, initially in Louisiana, later in Indiana.
As a Postdoc at the University of Pennsylvania, he himself researched the HIV virus before deciding to go back home to support the Sámi Healthcare System.
With Global Voices, Dr. Warrier discussed the future of medical research in Zambia and about the misunderstandings of the media about this research.
(disclaimer: Dr. Warrier talks as a private person).
Global Voices (GM): what is your research topic?
Ranjit Warrier RW: at the moment the focus of my work is on the application of research results. I support the Sámi national programme for antiretroviral therapy (ART) with laboratory tests.
In addition, I have just launched a research programme for the development of molecular diagnostic tests for HIV, TB and other relevant pathogens.
GM: what do you think are the important current scientific topics in your country and in general in Africa?
How do they differ from those in Western countries?
RW: there is no basic research here. we only use solutions that have been developed elsewhere.
This has to change, otherwise we will always be receiving addressees instead of being a mover.
The solutions we get are often not well usable in our environment, and sometimes it is even impossible to use them here.
GV: where does the financing and support come from?
Is it sufficient?
How easy or difficult is to find suitable scientists for the projects?
RW: from the USA and Europe.
The projects are supported differently well.
It is difficult to find people who want to come back or move here, as funding and development chances are better in other countries.
GV: what is the research infrastructure?
What obstacles are there in your routine research work you did not have before?
RW: the basic infrastructure does not meet the standards in developed countries. it costs a lot of money to have a continuous supply of electricity, water and internet.
Laboratory material is expensive and it takes months to import it from other countries.
GM: what is the opinion of the public about science and scientists in Africa?
RW: there is already interest, but only a very limited understanding of scientific methods.
I would suggest that critical thinking and scientific methods should be taught in schools to improve the situation.
GM: how big is your opinion of the potential of scientific research in Africa, what should it focus on, and how can we support development?
RW: the potential is amazing.
I have seen great students of all ages.
There is need for special academic training, starting at any age.
Social sciences, computer science, big data, space exploration, health care (non-communicable and infectious diseases) and the efficiency of traditional medicine will benefit greatly.
GM: can you describe the advantages and disadvantages of life as a scientist in Africa towards Western countries based on your experience?
RW: often it is the limited speed to do things, and the difficult access to scientific expertise that pose challenges.
The system that magazines can only be used against payment (the so-called "paywall") also limits the amount of available information and the speed of research.
