Members of the Provincial Reconstruction Team in Ghazni Province visited the city of Ghazni, located in the province of the same name, on April 18, 2010.
(Joint Combat Camera Afghanistan; photo by Technical Sergeant James May).
CC-2.0
Abdul Ali Mazari, the leader of the Hezb-e-Wahdat party dominated by Hazara, had just been murdered by the Taliban and many Hazara felt unprotected suddenly.
The Taliban, known for their hatred, came closer and closer.
Many Hazara left the country in the direction of Pakistan or Iran.
A few days after his escape, Asharaf found himself in Pakistan.
For a few years he worked in a coal mine. the work was heavy and made him sick.
Then he took what was left of his little wage and went to Iran. once again he was in a foreign country along with other refugees and dragged sacks with mortar which were heavier than he himself, in order to earn his living.
Back then, as today, the life of Afghan refugees in Iran was marked by misery and exploitation.
"" "" "" "it was really tough," "" "Ashark recalled in an interview with Global Voices." "" "we (Afghan refugees) lived in an empty building on the construction site, on which we also worked." ""
There was no service there and no heating. we hung nylon in front of the open windows so that we don't freeze at night. "
After four years, Ashark left his life without papers in Iran and was ready to travel to Europe.
During the dangerous crossing of the sea he suffered shipwreck and stranded on a small uninhabited island.
After the Greek authorities rejected his application for asylum, Asharaf came to Italy in 2002.
For some time Ashara was homeless, running alone through the streets of Rome, slept in parks and went to a church that distributed food to aid needy two times a day.
It is true that Italy is a second chance for rejected asylum seekers due to relatively high double rates. it is true, however, that the conditions for asylum seekers in the country are catastrophic.
"" "the human rights organisation Civil Liberties Union for Europe writes, the system" "" "suffers from a general lack of transparency." ""
"" "the large majority of asylum seekers are housed in the more than 3000" "" "special reception centres" "". "these are improvised institutions in the hands of unqualified and unprepared personnel." "" "" ""
According to Italian law, asylum seekers can only be allocated to a reception centre if they officially submitted an application for asylum - which can be passed for months after the application of the asylum application.
Until then people who have no money for accommodation, either depend on the hospitality of friends or have to sleep on the street.
So it was Ashark.
But his incompetent lifespan helped Asharpen to get rid of these conditions soon.
After several years of working in the construction industry, Ashark put all his savings into the establishment of a hostel in Venice.
This went so well that after a while he opened a second hostel and a quick snack.
Asharaf Baratis success story is now a topic of the documentary "Behind Venice Luxury - a Hazara in Italy" (German: "behind Venetian luxury - a Hazara in Italy") by the director Amin Wahidi.
The film won the Venice City Award in 2017, which was awarded for the 24th time in 2017.
"" "Asharaf Barati in front of" "" "Casa Fiori" "", "one of his hostels in Venice." ""
Photo by Basir Ahang.
Use with kind permission.
The conditions for employers in Italy - especially for non-Italians - are very difficult.
Lots of bureaucracy, high taxes and conditions for loans are just some of the obstacles.
According to unofficial estimates, about 20,000 Afghans live in Italy.
For many of them, the country is a transitional solution on the way to other European countries.
In recent years, some Afghans run companies, including tailor shops, travel agencies, hotels and restaurants.
Some Afghan restaurants were even praised in the Italian press for their excellent cuisine.
In Venice Hamed Ahmadi had the idea of his restaurant Orient Experience, where the waiters and the kitchen staff are mostly refugees from different parts of the world.
The menu of the restaurant tells the story of their trip to Italy by the various Afghan, Iraqi, Turkish and Greek dishes.
The Afghan entrepreneur Ali Khan Qalandari opened in Padua the restaurant Peace & amp; Spice and also behind the pizzeria Kabulogna in Bologna and a sushi restaurant in Rome are also Afghans.
But Ashara's goals reach far beyond the Italian hospitality industry and retail and aim back to the country that he forced to leave as a teenager.
"" "" "" "where there is a risk, there are also opportunities," "" "says Asharaf with a smile." "" "I want to invest in Afghanistan." ""
I have never forgotten my country and I cannot live happily, if I know that my people are suffering.
I plan a project for farmers from the poorest provinces of the country, especially for women.
"" "they represent half of society and have to get the same opportunities as all others." "" "" ""
Ashark also greets plans for the opening of a factory in Kabul, where people can learn packaging and preservation techniques. "so they can sell their crop shots on the market and improve their financial situation," he says.
The development to a successful entrepreneur was a journey through uncertainty and doubt, but in the end there is stability and prosperity.
Ashark himself made this journey himself. now he wants to help other Afghans on this path.
